Jack rolls 5 fair six-sided dice. What is the probability that at least two dice show the same number?
inference:
The probability of rolling any one number on a die is $\frac{1}{6}$. The probability of rolling two dice with the same number is $\frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} = \frac{1}{36}$. 

The probability of rolling three dice with the same number is $\frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} = \frac{1}{216}$. 

The probability of rolling four dice with the same number is $\frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} = \frac{1}{1296}$. 

The probability of rolling five dice with the same number is $\frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{6} = \frac{1}{7776}$. 

The probability of rolling at least two dice with the same number is 1 minus the probability of rolling all five dice with different numbers. 

The probability of rolling all five dice with different numbers is $\frac{5}{6} \cdot \frac{5}{6} \cdot \frac{5}{6} \cdot \frac{5}{6} \cdot \frac{5}{6} = \frac{243}{1296}$. 

Therefore, the probability of rolling at least two dice with the same number is 1 - $\frac{243}{1296} = \frac{1053}{1296}$.

Final Answer: $\boxed{\frac{1053}{1296}}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: The only way in which there won't be two dice displaying the same number is if exactly one number between 1 and 6 isn't being displayed on any of the dice and the 5 dice all display different numbers. There are 6 different possibilities for the number that isn't being displayed, and then there are a total of $5!$ ways in which the 5 dice displaying different numbers can be arranged, so there are a total of $6\cdot5!$ outcomes that result in the dice all displaying different numbers. Since each of the 5 dice can have 6 results when rolled and all of the rolls are determined independently, there are a total of $6^5$ possible outcomes, which means that the probability of all of the dice showing different numbers is $\dfrac{6\cdot5!}{6^5}=\dfrac{5}{54}$, so the probability that we want is $1-\dfrac{5}{54}=\boxed{\dfrac{49}{54}}$.
